        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/38021",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Note that this is a language behaviour.\r\nI don't think that we must mention within the manual how to code with PHP.\r\n\r\nSimply try the following:\r\n{code}\r\n$var = 1234567890123456789012345;\r\nvar_dump($var);\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nAs you see PHP itself converts numbers to float when they exceed a set value. When a number will be converted automatically is set by your PHP.ini configuration.\r\n\r\nThe reason why we can't simply say that floats are always digits is, that when someone really expects to get ONLY digits and we say OK for \"1.2345E-11\" then there would be a problem as there is a E and a - char which are no digits.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-01-25T11:04:21.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-01-25T11:04:21.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/38022",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Closing as non-issue",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-01-25T11:04:45.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-01-25T11:04:45.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/38039",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=cbuckley",
                        "name": "cbuckley",
                        "displayName": "Chris Buckley",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Hi Thomas, I know the behaviour of PHP and converting to floats, but this is a comment about the string representation of floats. I wouldn't expect that string '1.23456789012E+24' be validated by the class, as this would be wrong. But is it not at least worth mentioning that validating a float greater than 10^12 will behave differently than a float which is less than 10^12 but greater than PHP_INT_MAX? It might not be inherently obvious why 2147483648 validates but 1234567890123456789012345 doesn't.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=cbuckley",
                        "name": "cbuckley",
                        "displayName": "Chris Buckley",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-01-26T02:12:04.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-01-26T02:12:04.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/38069",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I don't think so... because this validator checks only DIGITS...\r\neven a integer with a negative sign is not valid as the minus is no digit.\r\n\r\nPeople working with such big numbers know what this works only with BCMath which means to have only strings.\r\n\r\nNote that \"Digit\" does not mean \"Number\"!",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-01-27T12:27:31.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-01-27T12:27:31.000+0000"
                }
            ]
        }
